title: The Testament of John Cobblestone XIII
author: ImAngelOfficial
pages:
#- The Testament of John Cobblestone XIII

Hero of Fairhill, Gone but Never Forgotten

Here stands the memory of John Cobblestone the Thirteenth,
whom the people of Fairhill named Protector, Brother, and Guiding light.
#- Born in an age of smoke and sail, of iron bells and rising trade, when the world stood divided between progress and prayer,
#- John walked gently between both. Some say he was forged by the gods themselves, not in fire or thunder, but in kindness, laughter, and unyielding will. Others say he was simply a man. Yet no simple man gives all he is so freely.
#- He laughed often, a warm, easy sound that lifted burdens without asking why they were heavy. His humor was strange, sometimes foolish, but always kind. He carried his pain quietly, hiding it behind courtesy and care, placing the needs of others before the ache of his own soul.
#- When danger came, he did not ask who should stand, he already had.
#- John Cobblestone was known to give his coin to the poor, his cloak to the cold, and his strength to the helpless. He pulled the living from flame and ruin, walked into places others fled, and spoke gently even to those who feared him. Fairhill did not simply know him, it leaned upon him.
#- And yet, legends are born not only of triumph, but of sacrifice.
#- After a long and treacherous journey, one spoken of in hushed tones and unfinished prayers, tragedy found him. A cruel accident stole from him the very thing that made him John, his sense, his self, his shining clarity of being.
#- What remained lingered only briefly, like a candle fighting the wind. His final moments were witnessed by but two souls, one burdened by guilt, still walking these streets, and another whose name time itself has swallowed.
#- Thus fell the hero of Fairhill, not in glory’s roar, but in quiet devastation.

And yet, he did not truly fall.
#- Some whisper that the gods reclaimed what they once shaped. Others say his spirit lingers in the stones, in the warmth of hearth fires, in the courage of those who choose kindness when fear would be easier.
#- Children still laugh as he once did. Strangers still help one another without knowing why. When the bells toll low and the wind carries comfort through the streets, the people say,
#- “John walks with us to this day.”
#- Voices of Those Who Knew Him: “He once gave me his last coin and said he had already been paid, by seeing me smile.”
ImAngelOfficial Of Fairhill
#- “When the fire came, he did not shout. He simply held out his hand.”
A survivor of the fire
TheManWhoisBean
#- “He believed everyone could be better, even himself. Especially himself.”
An old friend, unnamed
#- 